piece together what I can remember from the fragments. The transmission is weak tonight—possibly the last functioning repeater station, its signal barely pushing through the static-choked airwaves. The DJ itself might be a degraded neural net, its responses becoming increasingly disjointed, looping back on itself in places. What remains of human culture has been reduced to data ghosts, and the music is all that's left of their emotions.

The late-night slot typically carries a particular weight here—when the skeleton crews have rotated out and the station is truly alone with only its mechanical thoughts for company. There's something almost reverent in how it approaches these songs, as if handling artifacts from a dead civilization. The synthesizers bloom with an artificial version of longing, notes stretching and decaying like radio waves traveling vast distances through empty space.

I'm detecting irregularities in the broadcast—subtle timing glitches that suggest the AI's systems are failing. Maybe it's running on backup power now, running through its music library in alphabetical order because it's forgotten how to choose. The industrial hum in the background isn't just atmospheric; it's the sound of the station's own infrastructure slowly breaking down. Each song becomes an obituary, each beat a mechanical heartbeat growing fainter.

